dat$blockNr <- ""

  dat <- within(dat, CondFirstBlock[prolific_id == i] <- Cond[prolific_id == i & blockNr == "Block1"])

  dat <- within(dat, CondThirdBlock[prolific_id == i] <- Cond[prolific_id == i & blockNr == "Block3"])

#As there are lots of 1's let's see how often people scored 1's on average for A B and X (over all conditions)

#Create a subset of data with just the 1's in there
OnesR1 <- subset(train, train$responseR1 == 1)
OnesR2 <- subset(train, train$responseR2 == 1)
OnesR3 <- subset(train, train$responseR3 == 1)
#Take the sum of these ones over participants (as we want to know how often (on average) one participant scored a 1 for A, B or X)
SumOnesR1 <- aggregate(OnesR1$responseR1, list(OnesR1$prolific_id), sum)
SumOnesR2 <- aggregate(OnesR2$responseR2, list(OnesR2$prolific_id), sum)
SumOnesR3 <- aggregate(OnesR3$responseR3, list(OnesR3$prolific_id), sum)
#then take the mean
AvgOnesR1 <- mean(SumOnesR1$x)
AvgOnesR2 <- mean(SumOnesR2$x)
AvgOnesR3 <- mean(SumOnesR3$x)
AvgOnesR1
## [1] 16.44444
AvgOnesR2
## [1] 22.77778
AvgOnesR3
## [1] 5.666667

The average amount of 1’s given to A is 16, which is 33.3% of all trails, and 4 higher than in the original experiment.
The average amount of 1’s given to B is 23, which is 47,9% of all trials, and is 7 higher than in the original experiment.
And the average amount of 1’s given to X is 6, which is 12.5% of all trials, and is 1 lower than the original experiment.
You would expect that B is scored lower over all (as it’s the least predictive over all), and A to be scored higher over all, so have less 1’s than the rest. However what we see here is that X, the stimuli that always appears is actually scored 1 the least amount of times.
